## IMPROVEMENT 1 — PRESSURE-SENSITIVE STROKE SIMULATION

Currently strokes have uniform width. Real marker strokes:
- Start thin (pen touching paper, not yet pressed)
- Thicken through the middle (full pressure)
- Taper thin at the end (pen lifting)
- Have slight velocity variation (faster = thinner)

### Implementation

Replace the current per-segment uniform lineWidth with a
pressure curve applied per bezier segment:

```ts
// Pressure profile — bell curve with controllable parameters
function strokePressure(
  t: number,              // 0-1 progress along stroke
  opts: {
    peakAt?: number       // 0-1, where max pressure occurs (default 0.4)
    minWidth?: number     // fraction of base width at tips (default 0.25)
    sharpness?: number    // how quickly it peaks (default 2.5)
  } = {}
): number {
  const { peakAt = 0.4, minWidth = 0.25, sharpness = 2.5 } = opts;
  // Asymmetric bell: rises faster than it falls (like real pen strokes)
  const peak = Math.exp(-sharpness * Math.pow(t - peakAt, 2));
  return minWidth + (1 - minWidth) * peak;
}
```

Apply to every drawing primitive by rendering each segment
as its own beginPath/stroke call with computed width:

```ts
// In the animation loop, replace single ctx.stroke() with:
function drawSegmentWithPressure(
  ctx: CanvasRenderingContext2D,
  points: [number, number][],
  baseWidth: number,
  color: string,
  totalProgress: number,    // how far through the stroke we are
  pressureOpts?: PressureOpts
) {
  for (let i = 0; i < points.length - 1; i++) {
    const t = i / (points.length - 1);
    const pressure = strokePressure(t, pressureOpts);
    const width = baseWidth * pressure;
    
    // Velocity-based thinning: estimate speed from point distance
    const [x1, y1] = points[i];
    const [x2, y2] = points[i + 1];
    const dist = Math.sqrt((x2-x1)**2 + (y2-y1)**2);
    const velocityFactor = Math.max(0.6, 1 - dist * 0.003);
    
    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.lineWidth = width * velocityFactor;
    ctx.strokeStyle = color;
    ctx.lineCap = 'round';
    ctx.moveTo(x1, y1);
    ctx.lineTo(x2, y2);
    ctx.stroke();
  }
}
```

